04755nam a22007575i 9789633864388DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2022048157  a97896338643887 a10.1515/97896338643882doi  a(DE-B1597)633570  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU00aHD5854.2.I8bB488 2023 4aHD5854.2.I8bB488 2022 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a331.25/7290945223/eng/202211251 aBetti, Eloisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrecarious Workers :bHistory of Debates, Political Mobilization, and Labor Reforms in Italy /cEloisa Betti. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWork and Labor – Transdisciplinary Studies for the 21st Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments and Note to the English Edition -- tAcronyms -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER 1 THE OTHER FACE OF THE BOOM: THE DISCOVERY OF PRECARITY -- tCHAPTER 2 THE CONSTRUCTION OF STABLE WORK BETWEEN PARLIAMENT AND LABOR LAW -- tCHAPTER 3 STABILITY OR PRECARITY? THE TWO FACES OF THE LONG SEVENTIES -- tCHAPTER 4 THE MYTH OF FLEXIBILITY DURING THE ROARING EIGHTIES -- tCHAPTER 5 THE NEW EXPLOSION OF PRECARIOUS WORK BETWEEN THE NINETIES AND THE AUGHTS -- tCHAPTER 6 THE NORMALIZATION OF PRECARITY DURING THE YEARS OF THE GLOBAL CRISIS -- tEPILOGUE -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe recent vast upsurge in social science scholarship on job precarity has generally little to say about earlier forms of this phenomenon. Eloisa Betti’s monograph convincingly demonstrates on the example of Italy that even in the post-war phase of Keynesian stability and welfare state, precarious labor was an underlying feature of economic development. She examines how in this short period exceptional politics of labor stability prevailed. The volume then presents the processes whereby labor precarity regained momentum— under the name of flexibility— in the post-Fordist phase from the early 1980s, taking on new forms in the Craxi and Berlusconi eras. Multiple actors are addressed in the analysis. The book gives voice to intellectuals, scholars, politicians and trade unionists as they have framed the concept and debates on precarious work from the 1950s onwards. Views of labor law experts, politicians and public servants are investigated in regard to labor regulations. Positions of the very precarians are explored, ranging from rural women, industrial homeworkers and blue-collar workers to physicians, university researchers and trainees, unveiling the emergence of anti-precarity social movements. The continuous role of women’s associations and feminist groups in opposing labor precarity since the 1950s is prominently exposed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLabor marketzItaly. 0aLabor market--Italy. 0aTemporary employmentzItaly. 0aTemporary employment--Italy. 0aWorkxSocial aspectszItaly. 0aWork--Social aspects--Italy. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  alabor history.  aprecarious work.  asocial movements.  awomen’s history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2022z978311078048240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633864388?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633864388423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633864388/original  a978-3-11-078048-2  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA